{{Infobox medical condition (new) | synonyms = Hemangiomatous branchial clefts-lip pseudocleft syndrome | name = Branchio-oculo-facial syndrome | image = Autosomal dominant - en.svg | alt = | caption = Autosomal dominant is the manner of inheritance of this condition | pronounce = | field = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }}
'''Branchio-oculo-facial syndrome''' (BOFS)<ref name=Milunsky2008 /> is a disease that arises from a mutation in the [[TFAP2A]] gene. It is a rare [[autosomal dominant]] disorder that starts to affect a child's development before birth.<ref name=Milunsky2008>{{cite journal|last=Milunsky|first=Jeff |author2=Tom A. Maher |author3=Geping Zhao |author4=Amy E. Roberts |author5=Heather J. Stalker |author6=Roberto T. Zori |author7=Michelle N. Burch |author8=Michele Clemens |author9=John B. Mulliken |author10=Rosemarie Smith |author11=Angela E. Lin|title=TFAP2A Mutations Result in Branchio-Oculo-Facial Syndrome|journal=The American Journal of Human Genetics|date=9 May 2008|volume=82|series=0002-9297|issue=5|pages=1171–1177|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0002929708002152|accessdate=11 December 2013|doi=10.1016/j.ajhg.2008.03.005|pmid=18423521|pmc=2427243}}</ref> Symptoms of this condition include skin abnormalities on the neck, deformities of the ears and eyes, and other distinctive facial features such a [[cleft lip]] along with slow growth, [[mental retardation]] and premature graying of hair.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kulkarni|first=ML |author2=S Deshmukh |author3=A Kumar |author4=PM Kulkarni |title=Branchio-oculo-facial syndrome Pseudo cleft|journal=The Indian Journal of Pediatrics|date=1 August 2005|volume=72|series=0019-5456|issue=8|pages=701–703|doi=10.1007/BF02724081}}</ref>
== Signs and symptoms == "Branchio" refers to the [[branchial arch]]es, also known as the pharyngeal arches, of the affected individual. The branchial arches are structures in the developing [[embryo]] that give rise to certain tissues in the neck and facial area. In individuals affected by this condition, the branchial arches fail to develop properly. This leads to some of the physical conditions of this syndrome, which include abnormal patches of skin on the neck and face region and can be abnormally hairy, thin or red and with a high number of blood vessels.{{clarify|date=December 2013}} "Oculo" refers to the eyes. Individuals have [[vision impairment]] due to several malformations in the eyes such as small eyeballs, blockage in the tear ducts or lacking eyes completely. "Facial" refers to the face; those affected can have several abnormalities in that region. These abnormalities include a cleft lip, a [[cleft palate]] which is an opening in the roof of the mouth, widely spaced eyes ([[hypertelorism]]), sharp corners of the mouth that point upward, a broad nose that can include a flattened tip, along with several deformations of both the external and [[middle ear]] structures. This syndrome is restricted to the face, but it can also cause underdeveloped or malformed kidneys.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Raveh|first=Eyal|author2=Blake C. Papsin|author3=Vito Forte|title=Branchio-oculo-facial syndrome|journal=International Journal of Pediatric Otorhinolaryngology|date=30 June 2000|volume=53|series=0165-5876|issue=20|pages=149–156|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0165587600003104|accessdate=11 December 2013|doi=10.1016/S0165-5876(00)00310-4}}</ref>
== Pathophysiology and genetics == The disease is genetically inherited and stems from a mutation that deletes the [[TFAP2A]] gene. This gene is important because it provides the blueprint for the arrangement of 437 [[amino acid]]s that make up the protein [[transcription factor]] known as AP-2 alpha. This protein transcription factor binds to a carboxy terminus helix-span-helix motifand an amino terminus portion of DNA that affects the activity of numerous cellular activities such as [[cell division]] and [[apoptosis]].{{clarify|date=December 2013}} AP-2 alpha is especially important during the embyros development principally in the development of the branchial arches. Currently there are also four other proteins that are affected by the deletion of TFAP2A gene as well. One is [[L249P]], this protein changes to cause a conformational space change with a substituted [[proline]]. Furthermore, a change in the [[R254W]] and [[R255G]] proteins results in a replacement of a charged polar side chain by a nonpolar side chain,{{clarify|date=December 2013}} and lastly, an alteration in the [[G262E]] protein results in a nonpolar side chain being replaced by a charged polar side chain.<ref name="Milunsky2008"/>
== Diagnosis == Branchio-oculo-facial syndrome is difficult to diagnose because it has [[incomplete penetrance]]. It is often misdiagnosed as [[branchio-oto-renal syndrome]] because of their similarities in symptoms.{{mcn|date=December 2013}}
==Management== {{Empty section|date=August 2017}}
== Epidemiology == It was estimated that only about 50 cases of BOFS have been documented in the medical literature as of 2004.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wakehealth.edu/Health-Encyclopedia/Health-Topics/Branchio-Oculo-Facial-Syndrome.htm | title=Branchio Oculo Facial Syndrome | work=[[Wake Forest University]] | accessdate=12 December 2013}}</ref>
