{{italic title}} {{About|2006 ECHR case about termination for fatal foetal abnormalities|the teenager, Miss D, who travelled to the UK in 2007|Miss D}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}} {{Infobox European case |court=ECtHR |SubmitDate=11 July |SubmitYear=2002 |DecideDate=27 June |DecideYear=2006 |FullName=D v Ireland |ShortName=D v Ireland |ECLI=ECLI:CE:ECHR:2006:0627DEC002649902 |Chamber= |Language=English |Nationality=Irish |Ruling=Inadmissable |JudgePresident=Nicolas Bratza |Judge1=Giovanni Bonello |Judge2=John Hedigan |Judge3=Matti Pellonpää (judge){{!}}Matti Pellonpää |Judge4=Kristaq Traja |Judge5=Javier Borrego Borrego |Judge6=Ljiljana Mijović |Keywords=(Art. 1) Obligation to respect human rights, (Art. 3) Prohibition of torture, (Art. 8) Right to respect for private and family life, (Art. 10) Freedom of expression -<nowiki/>{General}, (Art. 13) Right to an effective remedy, (Art. 14) Prohibition of discrimination }}
'''''D v Ireland''''' is a case of the [[European Court of Human Rights]] concerning [[abortion]] in Ireland. It refers to the court case itself, and the circumstances surrounding abortion for fatal foetal abnormalities in Ireland. In 2002 Deirdre Conroy discovered her pregnancy was non-viable and had a termination in Northern Ireland. A public letter, written using a pseudonym, asking for it to be legal was credited with influencing the [[Twenty-fifth Amendment of the Constitution Bill, 2002 (Ireland)|2002 abortion referendum]]. She lost a court case in the ECHR in 2006 because she had not exhausted all domestic remedies. In 2013 after the [[death of Savita Halappanavar]], she came forward, revealed her identity and again asked for this sort of termination to be legal.
==Initial Letter== {{see also|Twenty-fifth Amendment of the Constitution Bill, 2002 (Ireland)}}
In January 2002, Deirdre Conroy was 39, the mother of two boys aged 10 and 12, and expecting twins. At 14 weeks pregnant, the initial results of an amniocentesis test revealed one of the twins had died. Three weeks later, full test results revealed the second twin had [[Edwards syndrome]], a condition which usually ends in miscarriage or death shortly after birth because of heart abnormalities, kidney malformations, and other internal organ disorders.<ref name="2013-05-03-irishtimes" />
In the run up to the [[Twenty-fifth Amendment of the Constitution Bill, 2002 (Ireland)|Twenty-fifth Amendment Referendum]], in February 2002, she wrote an open letter to [[The Irish Times]] newspaper, using the pseudonym Deirdre de Barra, telling of her case, and asking for termination for fatal foetal abnormalities to be legalised in Ireland.<ref name="2002-02-25">{{cite news|newspaper=The Irish Times|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/letters/referendum-on-abortion-1.1051700|date=2002-02-25|title="REFERENDUM ON ABORTION"|first=Deirdre|last=de Barra|accessdate=2016-07-26}}</ref><ref name="2002-02-26-irishtimes">{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/abnormalities-are-not-covered-in-amendment-1.1051731|date=2002-02-26|accessdate=2016-07-26|first=Kitty|last=Holland|newspaper=The Irish Times|title=Abnormalities are not covered in amendment}}</ref> [[David Norris (politician)|David Norris]] supported termination for FFA in that case.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/norris-lauds-courage-of-woman-1.1051894|newspaper=The Irish Times|date=2002-02-27|accessdate=2016-07-26|title=Norris lauds courage of woman}}</ref> Terminations for fatal foetal abonormalities were not covered by the Twenty-fifth Amendment referendum, and would have remained illegal regardless of the outcome of that vote.<ref name="2002-02-26-irishtimes"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/a-yes-vote-will-protect-doctors-1.1052032|title='A Yes vote will protect doctors'|newspaper=The Irish Times|first=Carol|last=Coulter|date=2002-02-28|accessdate=2016-07-26}}</ref>
The letter was credited with playing a part in the defeat of the Twenty-fifth Amendment referendum.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/the-year-between-the-lines-1.1107856|title=The year between the lines|newspaper=The Irish Times|date=2002-12-14|accessdate=2016-07-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/reasonable-compromise-beset-by-a-tide-of-controversy-1.1052966|title='Reasonable compromise' beset by a tide of controversy|first=Carol|last=Coulter|date=2002-03-08|accessdate=2016-07-26|newspaper=The Irish Times}}</ref>
She later travelled to [[Northern Ireland]] for a termination. The Irish hospital would not give her a referral letter, and her doctors were very guarded when discussing abortion with her<ref name="echr">{{cite court|url=http://www.bailii.org/eu/cases/ECHR/2006/1210.html|litigants=D v Ireland|date=2006|court=European Court of Human Rights}}</ref>{{rp|2–8}}
==Court Case==
===D's claim===
D complained about the need to travel abroad to have an abortion in the case of a lethal foetal abnormality and about the restrictions for which the 1995 Act provided. She expressly confined her complaint to the situation of a fatal foetal diagnosis, considering that her tragic situation was exacerbated by the above-noted limitations. She invoked Articles 3, 8 and 10 of the Convention. She further complained under Article 14 that she was discriminated against as a pregnant woman or as a pregnant woman with a lethal foetal abnormality: a person with a serious medical problem would never have encountered such difficulties in obtaining medical care and advice.<ref name=echr/>{{rp|58–60}}
===Ireland's claim===
====Domestic Remedies==== The Government maintained that, as soon as the diagnosis of Trisomy 18 was confirmed, the applicant should have initiated an action in the High Court, pursued if unsuccessful to the Supreme Court, to obtain a declaration that Article 40.3.3 of the Constitution allowed an abortion in Ireland in the case of a fatal foetal abnormality together with the necessary ancillary mandatory order.<ref name="echr"/>{{rp|64}}
====Possibly not illegal in Ireland====
The Irish government maintained that termination for fatal foetal abnormalities might not be illegal, pointing to the [[Attorney General v. X|X Case]] as proof that the [[Supreme Court of Ireland|Supreme Court]] could develop what "unborn" means<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Irish Times|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/foetus-may-not-always-be-an-unborn-argues-state-1.1030072|date=2006-07-14|accessdate=2016-07-26|title=Foetus may not always be an unborn, argues State|first=Carol|last=Coulter}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Irish Times|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/abortion-law-what-comes-next-1.1476187|title=Abortion law: what comes next?|first=Kitty|last=Holland|date=27 July 2013|quote=The State argued that the Irish courts were "unlikely" to interpret Article 40.3.3 "with remorseless logic particularly when the facts were exceptional" and that there was "at least a tenable" argument that an unborn with a fatal abnormality would not attract the protection of Article 40.3.3. She might have won had she gone to court in Ireland, said the State. The ECHR accepted the State's contention so found against her.}}</ref>
{{Quote|text=More centrally, it was an open question as to whether Article 40.3.3 could have allowed a lawful abortion in Ireland in the applicant's circumstances. The X case demonstrated the potential for judicial development in this area and, further, the X case did not exclude possible evolution in cases such as the applicant's: the foetus was viable in the X case whereas in the present case there might be an issue as to the extent to which the State was required to guarantee the right to life of a foetus which suffered from a lethal genetic abnormality. The meaning of "unborn" in Article 40.3.3 had attracted some public and academic comment (notably, the Green Paper on Abortion at paragraphs 35-38 above and a leading textbook on Irish constitutional law "The Irish Constitution", Kelly, at § 7.3.28). However, there had been little judicial examination of the meaning of "unborn" and certainly no case comparable to the present. Accordingly, although it was true that Article 40.3.3 had to be understood as excluding a liberal abortion regime, the courts were nonetheless unlikely to interpret the provision with remorseless logic particularly when the facts were exceptional. If therefore it had been established that there was no realistic prospect of the foetus being born alive, then there was "at least a tenable" argument which would be seriously considered by the domestic courts to the effect that the foetus was not an "unborn" for the purposes of Article 40.3.3 or that, even if it was an "unborn", its right to life was not actually engaged as it had no prospect of life outside the womb. In the absence of a domestic decision, it was impossible to foresee that Article 40.3.3 clearly excluded an abortion in the applicant's situation in Ireland.|source=<ref name="echr"/>{{rp|69}} }}
===Judgement===
The court dismissed the case, since D did not comply with the requirement to exhaust domestic remedies as regards the availability of abortion in Ireland in the case of fatal foetal abnormality.<ref name="echr" />{{rp|103}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/european-court-rejects-plea-to-hear-abortion-law-challenge-1.1026607|newspaper=The Irish Times|title=European court rejects plea to hear abortion law challenge|first=Carol|last=Coulter|date=2006-07-06|accessdate=2016-07-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/woman-loses-fight-over-abortion-claim-26373223.html|title=Woman loses fight over abortion claim|newspaper=Irish Independent|date=2006-07-06|accessdate=2016-07-26}}</ref>
==Later developments==
In 2013 after the [[death of Savita Halappanavar]], Deirdre Conroy revealed herself as Deirdre de Barra of the original letter, and the D in D. v Ireland, and spoke publicly about her case, and her experiences.<ref name="2013-05-03-irishtimes">{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/woman-at-centre-of-d-case-speaks-out-1.1381025|title=Woman at centre of ‘D’ case speaks out|newspaper=[[The Irish Times]]|first=Kitty|last=Holland|accessdate=2016-07-26|date=2013-05-03}}</ref><ref name="2013-07-11-indo">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/deirdre-conroy-i-dont-want-any-other-woman-to-go-through-the-ordeal-i-endured-29412093.html|date=2013-07-11|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]]|accessdate=2016-07-26|title=Deirdre Conroy: I don't want any other woman to go through the ordeal I endured}}</ref><ref name="2013-05-02-sundaytimes">{{cite news|url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/ireland/article1253595.ece%3FCMP%3DOTH-gnws-standard-2013_05_02&rct=j&q=&esrc=s|newspaper=[[Sunday Times]]|accessdate=2016-07-26|date=2013-05-02|title=My unborn baby was going to die. They said, ‘We can’t help you’|first=Justine|last=McCarthy}}</ref><ref name="2013-05-03-thesun">{{cite news|url=http://www.thesun.ie/irishsol/homepage/irishfeatures/4913521/I-kept-quiet-for-11-years-but-what-happened-to-Savita-was-the-last-straw.html|title=I kept quiet for 11 years but what happened to Savita was the last straw|first=Fiona|last=Wynne|newspaper=[[The Irish Sun|The Sun]]|date=2013-05-03|accessdate=2016-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Savita's tragedy brought back my abortion battle|url=http://www.herald.ie/news/savitas-tragedy-brought-back-my-abortion-battle-29238175.html|accessdate=2016-07-26|date=2013-05-02|newspaper=[[The Evening Herald]]|first=Cormac|last=Murphy}}</ref><ref name="2013-05-03-irishexaminer">{{cite news|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/a-very-real-tragedy-behind-a-human-rights-case-230194.html|title=A ‘very real tragedy’ behind a human rights case|newspaper=Irish Examiner|date=2013-05-03|first=Claire|last=O'Sullivan|accessdate=2016-07-28}}</ref> She requested to address the Oireachtas committee that was debating the [[Protection of Life During Pregnancy Act 2013]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2013/0502/389930-health-committee/|date=2013-05-13|title=Fianna Fáil defers abortion legislation support decision|publisher=RTÉ|accessdate=2016-07-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businesspost.ie/d-case-woman-wants-to-address-oireachtas-committee-hearings/|newspaper=The Sunday Business Post|date=2013-05-12|first=Niamh|last=Connolly|accessdate=2016-07-26|title= D case woman wants to address Oireachtas committee hearings}}</ref>
